$frontmatter {
  title: Hooks
  description: Named, typed async function slots for cross-cutting concerns — define once, compose freely.
  tags = ["hooks", "extensibility"]
}

"#": Hooks

"intro" = ```markdown
Hooks are named, typed async function slots. You define them inside a `#[hooks] trait`, implement
handlers with `#[impl_hook(...)]`, and the macro-generated owner struct dispatches them as a
fold or pick depending on the slot kind.
```

"toc".$toc = true

@ "define" {
  "##": Defining a Hook Set

  "body" = ```markdown
Annotate a trait with `#[hooks]` and place slot definitions inside it. Each slot definition is an
`async fn` with a default implementation:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::hooks;

#[hooks]
trait AppHooks {
    // "always": default runs first, then registered handlers chain on top.
    // The `last: Option<R>` parameter carries the previous handler's result.
    #[hook(always)]
    async fn validate_prompt(prompt: &str) -> Result<(), String> {
        if prompt.trim().is_empty() {
            Err("prompt must not be empty".into())
        } else {
            Ok(())
        }
    }

    // "fallback": if any handler is registered, use it; otherwise use the default.
    #[hook(fallback)]
    async fn pick_model(request_type: &str) -> String {
        "gpt-4o-mini".to_string()
    }

    // "singleton": last registration wins; emits a warning if overridden more than once.
    #[hook(singleton)]
    async fn cost_center() -> &'static str {
        "default"
    }
}
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
The `#[hooks]` macro generates an owner struct (`AppHooks`) with builder methods and a `new()`
constructor. Slot definitions live in the trait and are never visible at call sites — callers
interact only with the owner struct.
```

}

@ "implement" {
  "##": Implementing a Handler

  "body" = ```markdown
`#[impl_hook(SlotType)]` marks an `async fn` as a handler for a specific slot. The signature must
match the slot's arguments. For `always` slots, include `last: Option<R>` yourself:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::impl_hook;

// Handler for the `validate_prompt` always-slot
#[impl_hook(ValidatePrompt)]
async fn reject_api_keys(
    prompt: &str,
    last: Option<Result<(), String>>,   // carries the previous handler's result
) -> Result<(), String> {
    if let Some(prev) = last { prev?; }  // propagate earlier failures
    if prompt.contains("sk-") {
        Err("prompt looks like an API key".into())
    } else {
        Ok(())
    }
}

// Handler for the `pick_model` fallback-slot (no `last` parameter)
#[impl_hook(PickModel)]
async fn gpu_heavy_model(request_type: &str) -> String {
    if request_type == "code" {
        "gpt-4o".to_string()
    } else {
        "gpt-4o-mini".to_string()
    }
}
```

}

@ "compose" {
  "##": Composing the Owner

  "body" = ```markdown
Build an `AppHooks` instance and register handlers using the generated `with_*` builder methods:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
let hooks = AppHooks::new()
    .with_validate_prompt(RejectApiKeys)   // chains after the default
    .with_pick_model(GpuHeavyModel);       // replaces the default (fallback)

// Call a slot — dispatches through all registered handlers
hooks.validate_prompt("Explain recursion.").await?;
let model = hooks.pick_model("code").await;
```

}

@ "slot-kinds" {
  "##": Slot Kinds

  "body" = ```markdown
| Kind | Dispatch | `last` parameter |
|---|---|---|
| `always` | Default first, then each registered handler in registration order | Yes — carries previous result |
| `fallback` | Registered handlers (first to last), ignoring the default if any are present | No |
| `singleton` | Exactly one handler (or the default); last registration wins, warning on override | No |
```

}

@ "builtin-hooks" {
  "##": Built-in Hook Sets

  "body" = ```markdown
Lutum provides three pre-built hook sets for framework-level and adapter-level extensibility.
```

  @ "lutum-hooks" {
    "###": LutumHooks

    "body" = ```markdown
`LutumHooks` is passed to `Lutum::new(...)` or `Lutum::from_parts(...)`. It currently exposes one
singleton slot:

- `resolve_usage_estimate` — returns a `UsageEstimate` for a request before it runs. Override this
  to supply cost-based budget estimates from a custom pricing model or a usage database.
```

  }

  @ "adapter-hooks" {
    "###": ClaudeHooks and OpenAiHooks

    "body" = ```markdown
Adapter-specific hook sets configure provider-level request shaping:

- `ClaudeHooks` — passed to `ClaudeAdapter::with_hooks(...)`. Exposes slots for resolving
  thinking budget tokens (`BudgetTokensResolver`) and model selection (`SelectClaudeModel`).
- `OpenAiHooks` — passed to `OpenAiAdapter::with_hooks(...)`. Exposes slots for resolving
  reasoning effort (`ReasoningEffortResolver`) and model selection (`SelectOpenaiModel`).

These hook sets use the same `#[hooks]` / `#[impl_hook]` pattern as user-defined hooks.
```

    "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum_claude::{ClaudeAdapter, ClaudeHooks};

let hooks = ClaudeHooks::new().with_budget_tokens(MyBudgetResolver);
let adapter = ClaudeAdapter::new(api_key).with_hooks(hooks);
```

  }

}

@ "request-extensions" {
  "##": RequestExtensions

  "body" = ```markdown
`RequestExtensions` is a per-request opaque type-map. Use `.ext(value)` or `.extensions(map)` on
any turn builder to attach typed metadata. Hook implementations, adapters, and `ModelSelector`
implementations can read these values by type:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
struct Tenant(&'static str);

let result = session
    .text_turn()
    .ext(Tenant("eu-prod"))
    .collect()
    .await?;
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
This is the recommended way to pass routing keys, cost centers, or tracing metadata from
call sites into hooks and adapters without coupling them to application types.
```

}
